@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "3.3 Comments within HTML & CSS";
}

<div class="container">
    <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

    <p>The previous code includes exclamation points within the HTML, and that's all right. Those are not elements, those are comments.</p>

    <p>HTML and CSS give us the ability to leave comments within our code, and any content wrapped within a comment will not be displayed on the web page. Comments help keep our files organized, allow us to set reminders, and provide a way for us to more effectively manage our code. Comments become especially useful when there are multiple people working on the same files.</p>

    <p><strong>HTML comments</strong> start with <code>&lt;!--</code> and end with <code>--&gt;</code>.</p>
    <p><strong>CSS comments</strong> start with <code>/*</code> and end with <code>*/</code>.</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: HTML Comment</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            <pre><code class="language-html">
&lt;!-- This is an HTML comment --&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is visible content.&lt;/p&gt;
            </code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: CSS Comment</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            <pre><code class="language-css">
/* This is a CSS comment */
p {
    color: blue;
}
            </code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("BlockInlineElements", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-outline-primary">← Block vs Inline Elements</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("HtmlElements", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-primary">HTML Elements →</a>
    </div>
</div>

